        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/jim_cowan/{size}/495_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-03-28T01:01:35.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group quote-modified\" data-post=\"9\" data-topic=\"178168\">\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"7\" data-topic=\"178168\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>Burgundy is very confusing.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>And Chablis as a subset of Burgundy is doubly confusing. There are roughly 40 Premier Cru vineyards, covering an area of 1,915 acres (775 ha). In practice, there are only 17 Premier Cru names in common usage. The grower has a choice: he or she can either use the main premier cru name on the label\u2014and blend the wine from several subsidiary vineyards under this title\u2014or continue to use the old lieu-dit.</p>\n<p>In the case of Forets, the primary vineyard is Montmains. The lieu-dits in the Montmains vineyard are Forets and Butteaux. Raveneau produces both a Montmains and a Butteaux, but they could blend the wine from both locations, in which case the wine would have to be labeled Montmains only.</p>\n<p>Another example of this in practice at Domaine Raveneau is Montee de Tonnerre, where there are separate bottling\u2019s of Montee de Tonnerre and Chapelot most years, but in years of low production they don\u2019t produce the Chapelot and bottle the juice from that lieu-dit in with the Montee de Tonnerre bottling.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Some things are worth the effort.<br>\nYour knowledge is proof positive.</p>",
        "post_number": 10,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 11,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-04T14:13:49.748Z",
